<font color="#FF0000">JUST A THOUGHT</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 12 15:10:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all the Vets:<br>
     I just had to sit back and listen to all the emotions on this site-It is just incredible!!  (More emotion than a Italian wedding-That's not a racial joke, I'm Italian).  I was just thinking how many of the Vietnam vets I've known feel the same way as the guys on this site.<br><br>
Tom is right, Nam Vets need to realize how much of a leader they really are.  The lessons you learned in Vietnam (whatever they are-each man comes away with something different) are important and have carried you through God knows what.  Tom calls it right again, &quot;Their strength doesn't come from 'being right'.  It comes from being.&quot;<br><br>
Not to long again I read the book- Back From the Brink (Bantam Books 1992).  It's written by Don R. Catherall, a PH.D. in psychology, a Nam vet, and co-founder/director of the Phoenix Institute in Chicago, which specializes in PTSD.<br>
I think he best describes the Nam Vet.<br>
Catherall believes:<br>
1.  Nam vets are less likely to blindly accept the orders of others and perceptions of others.<br>
2.  Nam vets are more likely to measure others by their reliability (less on titles).<br>
3.  Nam vets are less hung up on appearances, less easily fooled and can see through BS better than others.<br>
I think these are lessons we all can benefit from, too bad more Americans didn't learn these lessons.<br><br>
Catherall also said of Nam vets, &quot;I think we share a sadness and a brotherhood that is rare.  It may not be a active part of our lives most of the time, but Vietnam vets are able to connect in a way that goes very deep.&quot;  He also wrote, &quot;Many of us have volatile tempers, seek adrenaline-rush-type activities, are workaholics, alcoholics, and are maintaining but still sitting on explosive energy. We know how to take orders and give orders. We have shared our canteens with all classes of people.  We've seen death close up.  We've experienced big-time loss.  We've faced our fears and found our own courage. As a result we are different in a way that the Indians understood and prized, but which our society does not well understand and often fears.  We have had the experience of being judge, jury, and executioner.  Many of us were free to take life without having to account for our reasons.  We were all effected by having that incredible power of living through an experience in which there was no law-we were the law.&quot;<br><br>
I thought Catherall has described Nam vets in a way they have not been too often described before.  I think the description certainly fits.  I had to share it with my father who is a Nam vet and he agreed.  I thought I would share it here.  I sill think that Nam vets are not the walking time-bombs that they once were portrayed as, but rather a integral part of the American society.  I think it is time for all Nam vets to realize they are different and how much that matter to us all.<br><br>

